Contracted COVID-19, was able to recover at home and today got to donate plasma to help other COVID-19 patients ❤️ #T1DStrong https://t.co/d9VFDX37da

@KaitlinCurtice I also contracted COVID-19 and was able to recover at home even tho I have an underlying condition. Though most will recover, the stories of those who don’t are heartbreaking. I’m grateful to be alive. We really are not promised tomorrow.

@KaitlinCurtice I also contracted COVID-19 and was able to recover at home even tho I have an underlying condition. Though most will recover, the stories of those who don’t are heartbreaking. I’m grateful to be alive. We really are not promised tomorrow.
Day 12 - 15: All symptoms persisted throughout the entirety of the 2+ weeks but lessened in severity with each day. Felt a little like I had a cold - stuffy nose, chest congestion again.
Day 11: Finally felt like I was improving. Breathing troubles eased just a little. Temp dropped back into 99s.

Day 5: Breathing trouble became increasingly worse and I started to have the dry cough that leaves you gasping for air. Temperature broke 100 for the first time. Decided to contact my doctor because I was getting worse even though I was on meds.
Day 3: Continued to lose appetite. Breathing troubles worsened but still just felt like bronchitis. Diarrhea started, which I initially thought was due to the antibiotic. Some queasiness.
Day 10: After being tested on day 7, I learned I was positive for COVID-19.

Day 5: Breathing trouble became increasingly worse and I started to have the dry cough that leaves you gasping for air. Temperature broke 100 for the first time. Decided to contact my doctor because I was getting worse even though I was on meds.

Day 2: Felt increasingly tired as the day went on. Cough worsened a tiny bit. Started to lose appetite. Did a telehealth appointment and was diagnosed with bronchitis. Prescribed antibiotic and inhaler.

Day 1: Slight cough developed late in the evening. Felt congestion in my chest so didn't think much of it. Checked my temp just for the hell of it bc of everything going on. It was 99 something. Had been feeling tired during the week.

Day 5: Breathing trouble became increasingly worse and I started to have the dry cough that leaves you gasping for air. Temperature broke 100 for the first time. Decided to contact my doctor because I was getting worse even though I was on meds.
Day 4: Felt about the same. Temperature still hovered in the 99s. Lost sense of taste. I can't say that I noticed if I lost my sense of smell - these weren't highly publicized symptoms at the time.

Since some people asked - I’m 34. Never smoked. Type 1 diabetic of 30 years in great health. Thankfully, my blood sugars were actually great throughout. Possibly because I was eating so little due to loss of appetite.
